  "prompt": "How much do gold medalist score in programs like MA Economics from IGNOU?",
  "response": "At IGNOU (Indira Gandhi National Open University), the grading system for programs like MA Economics is based on a numerical marking system that is later converted into letter grades. The specific scores required to achieve a gold medal can vary depending on the university's policies and the performance of other students in the same batch. \n\nHowever, to give you a general idea, IGNOU typically awards gold medals to students who achieve the highest overall percentage in their program. Here is a general overview of the grading system at IGNOU:\n\n- **90% and above**: A+ (Excellent)\n- **80% to 89%**: A (Very Good)\n- **70% to 79%**: B (Good)\n- **60% to 69%**: C (Satisfactory)\n- **50% to 59%**: D (Pass)\n- **Below 50%**: E (Fail)\n\nTo be a gold medalist, a student usually needs to score in the highest possible range, often close to or at the A+ level (90% and above) across all their courses. However, this can also depend on the relative performance of other students in the same program.\n\nFor precise information about the criteria for gold medals at IGNOU, it would be best to refer to the university's official guidelines or contact the Student Evaluation Division directly.",
